Russian President Vladimir Putin signed the law on the introduction of administrative responsibility for violation of the term and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) in the procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to address the very acute problem of non-fulfillment of obligations by customers in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already executed state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General’s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem on special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with dishonest customers who concluded contracts not backed by financing, tried in every way to evade the assumed obligations for payment and included in the contracts illegal conditions.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the Prosecutor’s Office has submitted 9.7 thousand submissions, according to the results of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials were brought to disciplinary responsibility, administrative - 533, 75 materials were submitted to investigative bodies for the organization of procedural checks, 46 of them were initiated criminal cases.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
Moreover, these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multi-billion dollar contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs by much more modest amounts have led to fabulous debts.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial burden on wages, taxes, and loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor’s office.
In some areas, the problem has been eliminated as much as possible.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, revealed by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt ratios continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor’s office operates under manual crisis management.
The Prosecutor General personally conducts field meetings with representatives of the local authorities, at which all violations detected by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination are dealt with.
Such operational meetings have already been held this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in the Part of Establishing Administrative Liability of Officials of the Customer for Violation of the Period and Procedure of Payment of Goods (Works, Services) in Procurement to Provide State and Municipal Needs" signed last week by the President of Russia will be able to qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences with an article that provides for a fine from 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment of goods, works and services for state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative amendments in practice.
Civil Rights Group Announces Moving Warning in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri because of the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement reads: “The National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population Travellers warning, valid until August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, guests and citizens of Missouri to be particularly attentive and cautious when traveling around the state in connection with a number of questionable racist-related incidents that have recently occurred here.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population, a recent Missouri law has made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the fact that state law enforcement agencies disproportionately often choose minorities as their targets.
“You are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, beaten and killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization against the U.S. state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas during a trip to the state, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office, according to which black drivers are 75 per cent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People must be prepared in one way or another, whether they take the money with them for collateral or inform their relatives that they are traveling through the territory of the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, there were 100 hate crimes in Missouri in 2015, making it the 16th most hate crimes in the state.
Also, the travel warning is a response to a new Missouri law, after which it will be more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity in connection with housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued warnings to travelers in Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration control laws that ordered local law enforcement to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said was supposed to increase the number of checks on racial grounds.
Movement warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but more recently, public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
