Trump’s White House is now targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when he begins to fight the statues.
Americans understand this no worse than everyone else - hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of the statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration’s key ideologues, no doubt knew what he was doing when he carried a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a fierce dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta over the president’s proposals to drastically reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't attack the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried to do so.
But he tried to find its meaning, and especially the meaning attributed to her in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when the poems of Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller murmured at Acosta: “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you’re talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.”
Miller correctly laid out the facts, but as he himself said, it’s not really about history.
This is about the current sound of the astonishing words of Lazarus, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds, dreaming to breathe freely, / the unfortunate scum of your abundant shores."
“Unfortunate waste” has never been so visible on our screens.
Miller did not do literary studies - he made it clear that these people are not expected in Trump's America.
This dispute over the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it is indeed a dispute over the meaning of America.
Lazarus – and her friends, who fought to put her words on the statue’s base after her death – understood very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Freedom.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The combination of poetry and image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though to change it back.
The thunderous Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist who announced the coming of Trump, reasoned in 2010 that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative, carrying the flames of America to the world lying in darkness: “Freedom is moving forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States.”
Against the custom, Limbo really got to the point here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she would be seen by exhausted, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often difficult voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who seek refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue responds to them with words of hope and hospitality that they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to light the way, but to inflame hatred, which is the only source of their power.
