Blocking Facebook Critics: Don’t Run for Public Office if You’re Not Ready to Listen to Criticism from Voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
The Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he didn’t shut his mouth to critics.
As Washington said in 1783, “Freedom of speech can be taken away, and we, the deaf and the dumb, will be led as sheep to the slaughter.”
Now I’m going to go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor’s subordinates called the lawsuit insignificant, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of “well and what”.
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But that's important, too.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a remarkably popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
It ranks second in the approval rating among the country’s 50 governors.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has shown a firm hand in running the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as a primary way of communicating with his constituents and jokingly shows off his bald head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and is run by the administration for taxpayers' money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chess defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply a moderation of comments.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters raging online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their chosen leaders.
They all say their comments were respectful, meaningful, and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lakshmi lawyer Sarma Ramana from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in a post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called screw-up, instead of admitting they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life position.”
In the era of Facebook, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is far less dusty work than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical advances, or arresting and shutting the mouths of protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to the U.S. District Judge from Alexandria James K. Casheris, the chairman of the Laudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by banning the voter from his Facebook account.
In Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It doesn't have to be that hard.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal spending was about as disruptive as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Portius" wrote letters to the newspapers ridiculing Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he didn’t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
