Poverty and Death in Indonesia’s “Golden Land”
When I'm cooking lunch, Bardina Degei doesn't use the stove.
She rarely even uses the pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just puts a sweet potato, which here is called a "note", right in the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tubers are removed and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the ground floor – she has no furniture – and it is here that she does her homework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many of the men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, raising their hands in public before the occupying forces.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which retains tight control over the region while preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes a one-and-a-half-hour flight from Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, to Nabira, and then a five-hour shake-up by a rented car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs are painted rusty in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians got here, not to mention journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Prior to the arrival of Christian missionaries, the mee pago papuas worshipped a god named Uga Tame.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” Degei says, pointing to her bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
This is Indonesia’s golden land.
The world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a mountainous province about the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves, the cost of which is estimated at $ 78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands of greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
Human rights activists say more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass killings in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” the report, published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – especially frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electric shock – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because accidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
Nuts were delayed as Papuan resources attracted an influx of immigrants from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of vegetables "gado-gado", served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to withstand the competition.
“Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than the indigenous people of Papua,” explains Abet You, a 24-year-old native of Paniai who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of work.
“Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua – the mom-mother (woman) of Papua – have lost their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequalities and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” he said.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration of Jokowi, Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas hymns at a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after some time returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Aimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later someone set fire to the nearby government building of the election commission, and the next day the situation escalated.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered on the football field in front of a local police station and a military command center to demand justice.
They brought ritual hunting bows with them and performed the vaita, the dance of the Papuan mee pago tribe: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation intensified, soldiers on internal radio were given the order: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” he said in an official document seen by TIME magazine but not published in local media.
Sixty-five-year-old Jeremiah Kayame, head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who shot, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
The local resident Alfius Jova was hit three times, as his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, tells us.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME.
“I saw him dead...I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, a senior police inspector in Papua, told reporters that his officers were only “defending” their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papua police spokesman Pujo Sulisiyo said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings only reached Jakarta the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a fervent speech in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Viranto said he would set up a non-judicial organization to put an end to historical human rights violations.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
“Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early zeros.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed,” he said.
Viranto then renounced his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through the court.”
Viranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during a bloody vote for East Timor’s independence in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the Paniai victims met with such statements with grim distrust.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there hasn’t been any change at all,” says Johannes.
“I’m tired.”
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid I’m going to get arrested by the military, I’m afraid I’m going to get shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the residents of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury the four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in the neighboring district of Deiyai.
A clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take a man unconscious to a hospital killed one person and injured 17 others, including children.
A man, 24-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the officers, who in response fired warning shots.
But local residents claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
"We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retaliation," said the 29-year-old Domingu Badia, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being rushed to the hospital.
“I stayed at home for two days.”
The parliament demanded that officers involved in the incident be called to account and a mobile police brigade be recalled from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development causes dissatisfaction of the meye, moni, dani and damal tribes scattered throughout the green central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to protect the rights of Papuans by arranging sporadic attacks and raids with kidnappings on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM's top leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and unreasonably detained by the military under the pretext of “defending national independence” in Paniai in recent years.
Some never came back.
Among the population of Papua, Paniai is considered a “sad, forgotten place”.
Poverty increases dissatisfaction.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is equally inaccessible.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly notes, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four to five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten tubers of note cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has increased between indigenous Papuans and new migrants who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
Few existing vacancies are usually available to more educated and affluent migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village...because there’s no work or money here,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, the restrictions on the work of international media remain rigid.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudy and Basile Longchamp were deported from Papua for “insufficient coherence with the relevant organizations” despite being given rare video permits.
According to Felim Kine, deputy Asia director for Human Rights Watch, the promises made during Jokowi’s election campaign to lift restrictions on media work in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Foreign journalists trying to report from rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua are now facing new dangers: visa waivers and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of attention from the press means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua’s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various and widespread violations” in Papua, including the shooting in Paniai.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanata Nasir dismissed the group’s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that “In Indonesia there is still a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights abuses.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch Ambassador for Human Rights Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local residents broke the silence, asking: “We want freedom,” according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokovi again.
“Jokowi is a man with good intentions but surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from the greedy army, are immersed in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobay says that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their voice given to Jokovi a duty that he must pay.
“They don’t want money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military site.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not allow the guilty to forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus says without raising his head.
“What else did we have to do?”
