EPA chief Pruitt refuses to delay Obama’s emissions reduction rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency canceled his decision to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted under Obama, designed to reduce emissions of substances that pollute the air and lead to the formation of smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that his agency is now more than under previous administrations, listening to the needs of environmental regulators of individual states.
He did not mention a lawsuit against his previous position filed in a federal appeals court.
The dispute unfolded around the October 1 deadline, to which the states must ensure compliance with 2015 standards for ozone at ground level.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone compliance by one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid “inconsistencies with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma’s attorney general before being appointed by President Trump, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental norms.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of norms that were opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industry.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Pewtt to return to the old norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA had exceeded his authority in an attempt to delay the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement issued on Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that, by drastically changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s duty to cooperate with the states in an integrated process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“Under previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet its deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed timelines in the course of settling the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through legal proceedings, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our charter and the authority it gives us.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt could at some point again use his “deferral powers and other powers given by law” to make sure that the rules “jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader revision of the rules on ozone.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay compliance with 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states filing a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue the legal pressure.
“The change in the EPA’s course – following our lawsuits – is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington D.C. joined the lawsuit.
Ground-level ozone occurs when ordinary pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries and chemical plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in people who are sensitive to it, leading to thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health and environmental advocates welcomed the sudden change in Pruitt’s course.
“It’s sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from the person charged with protecting the air we breathe,” said Lori Anne Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign to protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
