Morse Ford Murder: Activists Will Lose Lynch's Trials on Stage to Call for Justice
"Ford Mercury" in 1948 drove past the audience in the village of Monroe in Georgia and rushed with a roar to the small bridge Morse Ford.
As the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its way.
The main - a middle-aged man in a suit in a thin strip - pulled a cigar and looked through the windshield.
The people inside were trembling with fear.
"We need that nigger, Roger!" the man cried.
"Get him out of the car!"
The piercing cries broke the silence as a young black man was pulled from the front seat.
Thankfully, this horrible scene that took place on July 22nd is just a staging.
But when "Roger" was put on the neck of a loop, almost all the viewers really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have returned to the Morse Ford Bridge to replay the night the Kuklux Klans lynched two black couples – Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey – in 1946.
No one was convicted of these murders.
“It’s amazing that no people have been arrested in all these years — even though we see them next to us; even though we know who they are,” says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"It's a stain on our history and it's a stone on our souls."
Brooks, 71, is a former member of the Georgia Congress who has fought for human rights his entire life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to Monroe residents that injustice has never been corrected.
“We want investigation, we want completion, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he said.
“We cannot move on to healing and reconciliation until justice is done.”
The coroner covers the body of one of the lynching victims at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI materials obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always been well aware of two lynchmen’s motives: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time allowed black citizens to vote on the primaries that were due to take place that summer.
Around the same election, the FBI reported, black gunman Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says that Hester was rumored to have slept with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the baby she was about to give birth to was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 in bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they were driving out of prison and approaching the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of brigands surrounded the car.
“It turns out that he organized and commanded the murders Harrison,” – such conclusion is made in one of the FBI reports.
“It is also clear that there was a collusion between state and city law enforcement agencies, which not only took part in the murders, but also destroyed the evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses.”
Brooks calls it shorter.
“It was an attempt on voting rights,” he said.
“They were all killed to send a signal to the blacks in town: if you sign up and vote, it will be the same with you.”
For almost a decade, Cassandra Greene has been leading the annual lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is spectacular, captivating the audience and telling the story of that deep racism that many would like to believe is no longer in America.
It’s hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green thinks that’s what matters.
“We don’t want to talk about Lynch’s courts because they show us our own ugliness,” she says.
“But I can’t build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I’ve been through.”
Rehearsals for this year's play began in June, and on the first day almost 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - gathered in the room and listened to the polished over the years review of the play.
Wade Marbo was a director with Greene.
He played the role of the main member of the clan for several years, but says that the role has not become easier.
“I think I got dirty because that’s not the person I am,” Marbo says.
“But I think it’s very important to remember this story because we don’t want to go back to that time.”
In the room, Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
The spectacle begins with Malcolm, enraged that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Screaming Rascon in response.
It's a blow.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) is whining.
Greene laughs louder than anyone.
"What is it?" asked Ascona.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I overreacting?
"No," Green said, laughing.
"I just don't think white people said 'nigga' back then."
"Yes," laughs one of the black performers.
"You have to make a solid 'r'."
And so does the energy in the room: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone should do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the memory of four people killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Rascona says a word with the letter "n", it turns out to be clear and sharp.
No one laughs.
The show ends abruptly and quickly.
Shooting, screaming, and then silence.
A woman in mournful black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by the word.
In a hundred yards from it, half a hundred spectators wipe tears and sweat from their eyes.
Among the viewers almost equal number of blacks and whites.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to see the show; many live right next door.
They all endured the heavy spirit of Georgia for almost eight hours as Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of the Malcolms and Dorsey.
Until that point, the murders were just a story, but now that they are standing in the same place where people were lynching, it seems that their ghosts are floating in the air.
When the last note of the song fades, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children tilt to their heads, touch the paint depicting blood, and still bodies and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead," one little boy murmurs, as if to remind himself of it.
After a few minutes, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly everything is over.
Actors throw ropes off their necks and wipe away their tears.
Bradshaw embraces Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main puppeteer.
Nick Rascona hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the show finally fell on him.
“It’s okay,” one woman whispered.
“We know your heart is good.
You had a reason for that.”
Later, the audience sit down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta discusses a play with a black couple they just met.
Denise Daplinski struggles to find words to describe how she feels after the performance.
“It’s hard to listen to these horrible, horrible words and actions... people who look like you and who do it because they look like you,” she says.
“After that, I think lynching is still going on,” she adds, “only now it’s called police shooting.”
In the other corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks, who recalls his work as a human rights defender, got the general attention.
He says he has already started planning for next year’s show.
“The staging inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we’ve been through, but it also teaches us,” he says.
“Because if you don’t learn from this lesson, it can happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it.
