New results of tests to assess the age of asylum seekers in Sweden published
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, show that more than 80 percent of those tested were evaluated as persons over 18 years of age, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment of the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed they were minors.
So far, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were assessed as people 18 years of age or older, and for another 25 cases, the forensics agency estimated that the test subject was “probably a person 18 years of age or older.”
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person was “probably under 18”.
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person raises doubts.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with the results of the past months.
“We don’t see a big difference with the statistics of the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate,” he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases on which people were judged to be over the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, "most likely, the age of the tested 18 years or more."
However, after reviewing 581 published results, Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, a person openly stated that he turned 18 this year.
The method of conducting a medical age assessment, consisting of making an X-ray of wisdom teeth and a tomography of the knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and radiologists, also drew criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, Claude Marcus, part of whose work is to evaluate the biological maturity of people in order to determine whether they have passed through puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think you should use the measurement methods that are being used now.
The biological age is thus very inaccurate.
If we can’t define it with confidence, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told Metro.
However, Göranssen of the forensics agency spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, we can say that the risk of mistakenly accepting a child as an adult is small.
The biggest risk we face is when a person is soon 18, in which case he is about 10 percent.”
