The order and place of the oath will be determined by the President.
Where and how the new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law have been developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Building.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath in the law.
Children under 18 years of age, as well as those incapacitated, will be exempted from the solemn oath, follows from the amended text of amendments to the draft law "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (there is "Izvestia"), which the committee will consider before the second reading at its meeting on July 11.
The idea of introducing an oath when entering Russian citizenship instead of formal signing of documents, President Vladimir Putin supported on June 6 during a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies of the Russian Federation issued this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, which provides for the abolition of the decision on granting citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for the hijacking of a train or a train.
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: by issuing documents for citizenship, a person signs a promise to comply with Russian legislation - having embarked on the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
The draft law was submitted to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov ("Fair Russia") and the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Building and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the procedure for taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", specifying that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where it is possible to place the coat of arms of the Russian Federation is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, cabinets of heads of state bodies of subjects, municipal entities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could also be the squirrels.
To make a solemn oath wishing to obtain citizenship of the Russian Federation will be after the officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after taking the oath, follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text states that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, and not from 14.
There is a rule that the incapacitated or limited incapacitated, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or sign the text of the oath, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and “other persons”,
Also, the updated bill prescribes a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of residents of Ukraine, who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship, submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will have to be handed over to Russian officials.
The renunciation of “foreign” citizenship, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible “for reasons beyond the person’s control”.
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among which the first vice-speaker of DG Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, just impossible.
Accordingly, many people are waiting for the decision of their fate on the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the head of the Duma Committee on State Building and Legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (ER).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have writtenly renounced the "other" citizenship and handed over the previous passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond his control" he has not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be employed at facilities and in organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or residence permit of another country may not become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
