The National Health Service of England has announced that pre-exposure HIV prevention (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in at-risk individuals by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service for an initial three-year trial period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that claimed the National Health Service had the ability to pay for PrEP despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, which was announced on Thursday, was called a “major innovation” by National Health Service President Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Agency (NAT) called it a “turning point.”
Before the full launch of the program across England by April 2018, venereal dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to register people, and even more dispensaries will join the program in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking PrEP before sex in the human body, a sufficient number of certain drugs to prevent infection with HIV.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients entitled to receive the drug include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
The clinics will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals whose partners are not known whether their HIV status is inhibited by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and assigned to a general practitioner in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereal dispensary participating in the program.
The program will cost <0xC2><0xA3>10 million, and the National Health Service of England this week after an international procurement tender signed a drug supply contract.
The study is designed to assess all the possibilities of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who is the target audience of the drug, its digestibility and use on a large scale.
“This critical innovation should complement and intensify large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the greatest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT, said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at people in need and at risk, provides an opportunity to change the situation with the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study conducted in England at the expense of the National Health Service, will have access to a new opening up tool, the use of which a person can control himself without discussing it with a partner, which will lead to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.”
Ian Green, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “The first thing to do now is to make sure that the trial is rapidly rolled out across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is forgotten.
“Now that we are provided with the experimental drug PrEP, we are going to protect more than 10,000 people at risk for HIV.”
Shadow Minister of Public Health Sharon Hodgson said: “We very much welcome the start of the PrEP test, it is very late due to months of delays and delays from the government.”
