Judges offer protection from presidents
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judicial branch of power.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their election.
For courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The Human Rights Council has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the Human Rights Council on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with members of the Council.
At a meeting with the members of the Council on December 8, 2016, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as well as problems of public control in the places of detention of citizens (see "Kommersant" of December 9, 2016).
As a result of the work of the HRC, 25 proposals were made, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin’s human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, then the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, must submit him for appointment, not having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to distribute cases among judges.
This, experts admit, can be a specially written computer program.
Also, the HRC believes that the chairman has no right to "predetermine the results of the qualification attestation of the judge, initiate his bringing to disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to the “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and “to give them powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation”.
Now all the presidents of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to shield judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes to reorganize appeals and cassations in courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take the practice of arbitration courts as a basis.
There are “court districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials who have difficulty using the “telephone right”.
The Human Rights Council proposes to strengthen the people’s jurors in order to deal with certain “categories of civil and administrative cases”.
For example, about deprivation of parental rights, about recovery at work, about protection of honor and dignity, about deprivation of a driver's license, etc.
“These are just our proposals,” explained the “Kommersant” member of the Human Rights Council, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara Morshchakov.
She also recalled that the President's order was not only for the HRC, but also for the Supreme Court (SJ), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the execution of the order with the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in Russia, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must by September 1.
Living a high life: the semi-floor and cunning design techniques turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious home in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a pretty Queen Anne-style house, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not pack her things and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area,” Joan says.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price the same day.”
Since the first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete reconstruction.
Initially, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to squeeze the maximum benefit out of the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill-based architectural and design studio “Duck & Shed” to use ceilings 12.5 feet high and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would fit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to arrange two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-floor where one could stand in full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and did not have to bend.
It was necessary not only to build a simple platform, but also to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the premises from above and below.
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one above the other in the allocated space – and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" overlooks the chic living room below.
Mirrored furniture with gold finish, silver accents and vintage lighting from Serge Mui set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space, and light.
A short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored protective panel appears as a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a feeling of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can enclose the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in the kitchen.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding door, like in a garage.
"Engineering art was involved here," Erfan will tell about the reinforced steel of the wood-fiber shield door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Due to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
“After all, floor space is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued for,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will enter and make calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they were able to increase the floor area, using high-quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help build an emotional connection with the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This is a testament to the fact that due to a good design and an increased meter, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
