Italy is tightening its tone against NGO ships that rescue migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs owned by rescue vessels in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin-based daily Stampa.
Minniti’s warning came a day after Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization “Jugend Rettet” on suspicion that its crew actually cooperates with human traffickers and facilitates illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which worked for only a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against her by the Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
“For us, saving human life is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone right now,” the organization said in a statement.
“We will only be able to assess all the allegations made now after we have gathered all the information and been able to assess the situation.”
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventus vessel, owned by the Jugend Rettet, since October.
His crew is suspected of taking on board whole lifeboats of migrants, who were sent directly to them by human traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave along with boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the indictment, the content of which was published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the Italian coastal authorities’ regulations, which control rescue operations in the area, rather out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct assumes, mainly, that Juventa-type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: “Save the Children”, the Maltese MOAS and “Pro-Activa Open Embraces” from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considers the new rules unnecessary but acceptable, provided they do not entail any "significant changes or disruptions" to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In recent days, we have started to see light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He announced plans for further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
