The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have been frequented with visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Dengov told “Kommersant” what goals Moscow is pursuing in this region and who it is betting on.
Almost nothing is known about the Libya contact group you are heading.
Here, say, the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was created on the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya. - "Kommersant").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the formation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mechanic Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board.
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did it happen that you were the one to lead her?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the work of the group.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanics.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict, both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Saraj is based) and from Tobruk (the seat of parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya).
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Kommersant"), we managed to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
It was then decided to create a contact group in order to make more effective use of these contacts.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
In Libya, we do not want to be associated with either side of the conflict, we are in dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are currently five people in the contact group.
Among them there are people who have experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to include representatives of the Middle East Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences in the group of specialists for the region.
There is no permanent presence of our staff in Libya, which is not yet necessary.
Are there Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities like Misurata (where militias are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly intensified in subsequent years).
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were scared, they said that there are Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the role of Islamists in there.
In Misrata we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016 this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the banned in Russia "Islamic state" - "Kommersant").
We wanted to look at them, meet these people, check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed himself to these merits.
And what conclusion did you come to?
Didn’t the Islamic State in Libya win Haftar?
He didn't do it.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, Benghazi.
And with ISIS in Sirte fought the structures subordinated to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited the people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation to Russia.
And they came - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and Rosgvardia.
You, as we understand, go to all the Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj reached at the end of July in Paris?
Or again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, agreements will be broken, fighting will resume, the parties will try to take power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was boarding the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata, they didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, “You must be very brave people to come to us today.”
But our task is precisely to show that we do not only support Haftar, we are in dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar spoke.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR facilitates mutual understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
Russian, if he knows it, is very relative.
But the fact that he learned from us, of course, facilitates dialogue with him.
And not just with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak beautifully Russian.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they are nostalgic for it.
Do you think it is likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and do not want to arm one at the expense of the other.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, the Libyans are constantly calling for Russia to somehow contribute to its lifting.
In Libya, the process of drafting a constitution is being actively promoted.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve an internal consensus.
Then the elections should be held, as was also said at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If elections are held and a legitimate power is finally elected (and now neither side has such status), then it is possible to raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
To raise this issue is now pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by the fate of the allies of the EU.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic, for example, is the possibility that Haftar’s troops will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers smuggling immigrants to Europe?
Very timely question.
We are actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia’s support because Moscow is in dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata and the south.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the fact that the South stops the flow of migrants in the long run?
That is, conditionally speaking, turned back the buses, which are traveling Nigerian migrants?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to contribute to uniting the South in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the South.
But first, we would like to see unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Saraj.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia norms in the country.
How radical are his views?
Will this be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
Islamists are in the coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be a completely normal country – moderately Islamic, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
How did he get such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial powers are located.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not to climb there.
And we mixed all the cards with them and began to actively communicate with Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft’s head Igor Sechin made the deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil by Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess I'll resell.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
They are planning to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about the previous agreements in the field of transport (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, we are talking about the scheme of "oil in exchange for services"?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not deal directly with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work there.
For us, the main thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to agree among themselves so that they can establish order and that Libya ceases to be a conducive environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task – to help the Libyan people and push out the terrorists.
Do you have information about the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date, there are no natives from Russia and other countries of the former USSR there.
He said he has about 50,000 phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Kommersant") and Russian speech does not sound there.
What countries are these militants from?
I don't want to go into that detail.
Then we will formulate the question differently.
How many Islamic militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are almost no Libyans among them, they are no more than 5%.
The rest are incoming.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks on the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are in active negotiations with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow and have declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say now.
There are still several visits to be made, and then, hopefully, there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
