Michelle Carter's Sentences for Reports That Caused Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two-and-a-half years in prison for inciting her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months behind bars and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at a hearing on Thursday: “My family is grieving.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large until appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, squeezing her hands and lowering her eyes.
“She killed Conrad Roy with her actions,” the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve her own.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter’s lawyer said it was a “tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said he believed her "age, maturity level or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read out Roy’s mother, Lynn Roy, saying: “There hasn’t been a day that I haven’t mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I handle it - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever."
Roy's sister, Camdin Roy, said she was relentlessly haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
“Leaving the person who has always been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that provides responsibility for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been pushed to suicide by Carter’s message.
“You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don’t know a lot of ways,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the ignition and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention through Roy's death, and forbade her to communicate with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers are divided on this.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British flatmate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old wrote in the Los Angeles Times, “Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison.”
