A study conducted at the Expert-Criminalist Center found that it was fake.
According to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia in the Astrakhan region, the banknote was paid by one of the visitors of the cafe, who bought shawarma.
It is worth noting that the cash register was not equipped with a device for determining the authenticity of banknotes.
Currently, police officers are identifying persons involved in the manufacture and sale of a knowingly fake ticket of the Central Bank of the Russian Federation.
Such crimes are punishable by imprisonment for up to 8 years with a fine of up to 1 million rubles.
The Regional Office of the Ministry of Internal Affairs urges residents of the Astrakhan region to be attentive when carrying out financial transactions; employees of trade objects are recommended to install devices to verify the authenticity of the received funds.
Astronomers have found a "hell" planet on which even iron can melt
After studying for the first time the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysicists were quite surprised by its temperature, which is able to evaporate iron and other metals.
Experts noted that the water molecules are so heated by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Space Telescope has captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature causes water in the planet’s atmosphere to glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to the so-called "hot Jupiters" - gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the solar system, but located ten times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, the year on the exoplanet lasts only 1.3 "earthly" days, and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and southern France, but now there are fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender began to grow worse due to dry weather and disease-carrying insects; this caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert at the Provence-based agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: “Lavender in Provence is really under threat because in recent years this plant has been experiencing the effects of climate change: there has been much less rainfall in the spring and especially in the fall.
This affects the life of lavender.
And there are small cicadas jumping on the leaves of insects carrying micro-bacteria; in very dry weather, they become very much.
There is a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is very popular in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Shes says, “Instead of very long ears with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or absent at all.
Therefore, we have fewer parts that contain essential oil.”
Solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding varieties that are more resistant to drought.
