The journalist’s murder underscores that Mexico is becoming increasingly dangerous.
Employees of the weekly newspaper Riodos usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in Sinaloa state involving organized crime, corrupt officials, or the ongoing war of drug dealers.
But today, depressed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told that they had to change their habits.
The two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children to the office where the grenade had already been thrown in 2009 or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on a board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no evidence needed, suspicions and internal feelings will be enough.
These are drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being held by the government or cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who make the work of covering up the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence is respite, and among the corpses that multiply in the country, more and more journalists: according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, the co-founder of "Riodose" Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his numerous books on drug-related violent crime.
His absence is felt very sharply, although his presence is ubiquitous - a large photo of Waldes, showing the middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the building "Riodose"; two 30-year-old reporters, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts depicting his smile, face in the eyes or face in the eyes.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their general trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor’s office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders committed each year involving drug trafficking and organized crime, killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are killed by grief, although the environment is now much more dangerous.
“Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about security at meetings, there is little use,” Ibarra said.
"It's very stupid to waste time in this seminar," he says.
“Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone.”
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodose office in the state capital Culiacane.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper - which means "Twelveth River".
The shooter drove off in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually diverge quickly across Culiacan.
But about Waldes almost everyone is silent.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the United States in January last year, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlefields in the country as rival factions struggle to fill the resulting vacuum.
Not to mention that one or more people are killed every day in the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug lords, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let’s forget for a moment that the state of “calm” is simply when one of the cartels takes control of the coastal state with important ports and routes of drug trafficking leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorkes, a 60-year-old co-founder and director of R<0xC3><0xAD>odos, is crushed by guilt for not being able to protect his friend.
He thinks the murder was helped by two mistakes.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is fighting with the sons of Guzm<0xC3><0xA1>n.
The publication may have pissed off the sons; people who were supposedly gang members bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he didn’t force Waldes to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper was seized, which wrote about the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be there.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroest and in 2003, together with five colleagues, founded R<0xC3><0xAD>odos, selling his 50-dollar shares.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to engage in journalism without touching on the topic of drugs,” Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation as a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this publication they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, R<0xC3><0xAD>odosé received the prestigious Maria Murs Cabo Award for reporting in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his bravery in investigating drug trafficking in Mexico, wherever it led.
