On that day, Director Bohorkes was in Washington, D.C., trying to gain international support in demanding justice in the Waldes case.
At a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after the murder of Valdes, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their murders for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to give her any more assignments to cover the government’s activities, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdez has said many times that journalists in Mexico are “surrounded” by organized crime, its accomplices in the government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just being killed by gangs of drug traffickers; they are doing so on orders from politicians and security services in collusion with organized crime.
The Committee to Protect the Press, Article 19, estimates that half of last year’s attacks on journalists were ordered by police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,” Ramirez says.
Of course, murder scares people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Masias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
On her body was found a note allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I'm here because of my articles."
