Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, although it is horrifying.
The researchers said the first remains of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner were preserved so well that experts called it the “Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown—and to say that he had, in a way, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as “the best-preserved of Thyreophores in the history of the finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition stunned researchers who called him “really remarkable.”
This herbivorous thyrophorus is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Sancor Millenium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed to be different from the surrounding breed, and decided to look more closely.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to find the animal inside the earth's lump weighing 2,500 feet (1,100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
“It’s only worth a little peeping, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is demonstrated.
“It will go down in history as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved dinosaurs, the Mona Lisa amongst the dinosaurs.”
Studying its skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite the fact that it was covered with a shell and resembled a walking tank, apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerful shell-covered dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective dye, which is also used by many animals of our day.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with the surrounding environment and avoid encounters with enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaurus family, was widely covered in print in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and gave it the name Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of the museum laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours on his diligent excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and shell plates on his body.
They found a protective coloring, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its lower side.
Although the protective coloration is well-known, the discovery came as a surprise, because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of the now-living animals with the protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred masking confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with a protective coloration – such as deer, zebras or armadillos – are much smaller and more affordable prey, indicating that the nodosaurus had to fight seriously for survival.
“The serious threat from predators to the massive, powerful shell-covered dinosaur shows how dangerous the predatory Cretaceous dinosaurs were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur’s scale also suggests that its skin should have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, he fell into the river and was taken to the sea, where he sank and with his back down lay on the bottom of the ocean.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and the rivers and oceans were likely to have spread much further inland than they are now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered by the preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to recreate it, you just have to pee a little, and you can almost believe it’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous Period is an era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, the Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than the Borealopelta, the thyreophore may have been hunted by some of its formidable ancestors.
These include the acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5-metre)-long monster weighing six tons.
The scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was taken to the sea after his death and mummified in the mud.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to museum officials, this is the best-preserved thyroid in the world, along with the skin and shell, and it is intact, from the snout to the femur.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
The researchers believe that this herbivorous thyreophore was difficult to step on what is now Canada, until a flooded river carried it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur’s underwater burial preserved its shell with precision to the smallest detail.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur's skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is “rare as winning the lottery.”
The longer I look at him, the more striking he seems.
Fossilized remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates that sow the animal's skull.
His right front leg is stretched along the side, five fingers on it are turned upwards.
I can count the scales on his sole.”
