How did one activist find out the answer to the question “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York as part of a tourist trip, a native of St. Louis was sitting on a bed in an apartment rented via Airbnb, watching a Facebook feed on her phone.
She bumped into someone in high school.
“The police just killed an 18-year-old child, and he’s still in the middle of the street.”
Noticing that no one else in her tape had posted this information, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
She had a lot of user reposts with the nickname <0x40>TheePharoah.
The rapper from Greater St. Louis tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown’s lifeless body spread out across the street, where it would be for four hours.
“It’s wild,” Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put down her phone, and later in the evening returned to tweets that people were going to Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of the signal tape and screaming people and the man claiming to be Brown’s father holding a poster saying, “A Ferguson policeman just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, took the gun and shouted, "I will kill you all... animals!"
“It’s a non-standard situation,” Ferrell said in her memoirs.
“This is not a murder like the ones we’re used to and what we might call typical.
At that moment I felt a chill.
I was angry and crying.”
She took a return flight ticket and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father’s house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years was the subject of a new documentary, “Whose Streets?”, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and perseverance from the point of view of the people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrell was traveling to Ferguson with her daughter dressed in a flower dress and a wreath of color, they recalled a conversation they had had countless times before this morning, “about the experience of the blacks and their position.”
She recalls saying, “Remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We're going to Ferguson right now because a police officer killed an 18-year-old boy, and that was wrong."
“I couldn’t help it,” Ferrell said later.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what was happening before.
She needs to know about it, see it, and grow up on it.
She must not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their position and what we must do to become free in order to be free.
Even if I can provide her with an environment where she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would have done her a bad service if I had shielded her from it.”
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florissant Road, a site across the street from a police station that had become something of a tent camp, while activists waited for reports of Officer Darren Wilson's final innocence.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur who prepared lunch packages.
They collected packages and helped to distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little, Ferrell’s consciousness took shape as a new type of activism.
“My activism has completely changed since August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Sanitary Students, members of national minorities, and engaged in food justice and health inequalities among black communities.
“I have no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at the evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her main cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Ferrer "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question, “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?”
This skepticism was prompted by numerous people, often white, who came to the community in order to benefit from his pain and perseverance.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don’t get the spotlight and wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for her activism on death row issues.
His involvement aroused sympathy for the project among Ferrell and six other locals, with whom the “Whose Streets?” project team kept in touch during the years following Brown’s assassination.
“In this documentary, there’s no one talking for us or with us, that’s what we’re saying,” Davis said.
“It was the most important thing for me how these people will be represented, because that’s how I will be represented.”
And while the goal of the project was not to focus on Ferrell’s experience at all – to show that the movement “is not about the leader-savior, but about how the community unites,” Folayan said – it turned out to be the most open of the film’s participants.
As a result, "Whose Streets?" reveals unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, laughing at the first time she saw the finished product.
“But I understood that when you do that kind of work and humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell’s story again discusses and highlights the role of black homosexual women in the broader context of the “Black Lives Matter” movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement – those who created the tag #BlackLivesMatter on social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 – identify themselves as gay.
“Black gay women in leadership positions support this whole movement,” Ferrell says, “and all because we’re constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black homosexual women have to bear all this burden.”
Folayan agreed with the statement, noting that “the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of gay black women.”
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination" and that Ferrell was not chosen as the film's central character because of her distinctive features.
“She was the person who awakened that energy,” she said.
“On the other hand, it’s not a coincidence that she came to the fore, because when”
You can feel its energy through the screen.”
In Ferguson, meanwhile, there are no cameras, but complex racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell will be on probation for two and a half years for blocking the highway during the demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place she calls home, simply: “Bardak.”
She's still clinging to the language she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
