Emergence of similarity: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall at the Freedman Gallery in New York, people's faces hang from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all imperceptibly similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek strokes and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transmission of confidential diplomatic telegrams to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called “The Emergence of Similarities”.
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident, whom Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
Analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning with a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that could be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, though difficult-to-perceive manifesto dedicated not only to the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinism of these interrelationships.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward but has since adolescence openly said she considers herself a woman, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photos in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, on which Manning in a platinum-tinted wig, clearly feeling uncomfortable, is sitting behind the wheel of a car; with this photo she began to be associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project "Vision of Strangers".
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some kind of portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new exhibition.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited and photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait created from her DNA.
In such an unusual way, the artist and her jailed muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote the comic book Depressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, who portrayed how in the future the president would ease Chelsea's punishment and she could visit the exhibition in person.
That Obama really decided to release Manning just days after the book was released was a pleasant surprise after seven difficult years in a military prison in Kansas.
There’s something profound and powerful about the show opening right now, as Donald Trump declares war on people who reveal classified information in government, and invents new ways to inflame on Twitter the enmity he’s meant to soften.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that "nothing happens by chance."
In a statement written on the gallery wall, Manning’s huge signature downstairs (with a heart instead of a dot over the “i” in her last name) calls for an end to “the automatic division based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.”
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of C, G and A pencils.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist scientifically elegantly puts it), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how amazingly similar we are, at least in our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn’t define what we are, how open genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is,” Dewey-Harborg said in her 2007 video, “False Memories,” also featured here.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exposition, which fits in one room, is the above-mentioned novel in comics.
On it, King Kong-style Manning appears above the US Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
“So never shut up.”
“This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,” says the artist, who welcomes us from Philadelphia.
"I still have ants on my skin when I talk about it."
Manning had not yet seen the exhibition in person – as it was visibly depicted in the comics – but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacrums gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, as everyone at the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning height), on which the pencil was drawn genetic haplogroups.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like the movement that stood behind her release.”
