Startups that will help your company not to become another “Uber”
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among the employees of her startup in the field of e-commerce, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs the San Francisco-based 75-person Madison Reed, an e-commerce hair care company.
Therefore, she appealed to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of startups in the field of work with staff, which help companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee involvement, they allow companies to make express surveys, contact certain teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to pass top management and contact the directorate directly.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, and where’s Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City’s startup Glynt, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has gained a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel in the three years she has been using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in a visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies gradually realize that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another “Uber”, who was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post in which he described an aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the online portal “Let’s talk about payment” dedicated to financial technology, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight surge in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber’s declining reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, “Uber” appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom-made staff opinion polls, collect confidential responses in real time, and view thermal maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company treats employees badly or behaves unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a chain of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees across 500 establishments, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures, and to offer an easy way to contact the company’s head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a phone number or e-mail of the head office, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of law at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can come closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who heads the risk management group of the Ruby Tuesday network.
“And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Quinnland, companies began taking employee ethics, values, and engagement more seriously in 2002, after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron case.
But it wasn’t until “social media” became widespread that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty laundry from virally spreading online.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company’s total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing volume of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they used to.
In markets with tough competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, this is just a necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and valued, and that they devote their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work at a company, they feel they are being heard, and the work they do brings results, they are more committed to making it a success,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global employee benefits and satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors make an income when businesses from their portfolio are doing well; businesses are doing well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee involvement.
But the data is useless until the company’s trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can give the impression that changes are coming.
And if changes do not come quickly enough, or do not come at all, may develop disappointment, and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 proposals, you should be willing to have 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make a mistake relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, the staff will be wondering, ‘Did you really hear me?
You don't care?
If you don’t care, why should I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem using Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
“Ruby Tuesday” is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it to more effectively retain employees in an industry known for high turnover of personnel.
“If you’re not trying to create a culture of transparency, you’re going to lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose companies.
