Create a comic book novel: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, the tiny Scottney Castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cosy location in the Beale River Valley in Kent, he watched the turbulent history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with land hair and a penchant for historical documents, to a comic book novel.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says.
"You feel so personal when you hold this letter in your hand."
Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about the families that lived in Scotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabelle Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes’ first book based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of documents from the British Library; this project unexpectedly touched him to the core.
“I could have been touched by a simple fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those days they lit a fire for lighting.
And in 300 years, in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
I love the archives!"
For a person who has such a passion for old papers, to get support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and live in the castle for four months (“Frankly, I’m a little hospitable there”) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes studied the "new" Victorian castle all day, went through the archives and looked at the numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that lay in the ditch for centuries.
He walked around the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then at night he "drinked whiskey and sat down to write."
The history of Skotni Castle is not very well studied, because the National Foundation only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hassey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the staff were just beginning to deal with the archives, which he describes as “what the aristocrats had been putting down on the attic for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think the land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but two families fought for this birch.
It happens, guys!”
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for broader explorations in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is information about a riot that occurred in the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex,” says Rhodes.
“The Peasant Rebellion began in these places, and I thought the rebellion was a good start.
“Maybe they were connected?”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle, such as The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "Smuggler", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrel, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stuffing the coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug).
The Darrells are Rhodes’ favorite family of all who inhabited Scotney: “Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect jewel, always in debt and spending money on things they couldn’t afford.
In different generations, men-Darrels solved their debt problems by marrying rich older women - I imagine them as a company of cute guys who know how to care for the heirs of great fortunes.
After graduating from Castle Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamyanmäki - a place where at the beginning of the XX century there was a sanatorium, and then it was again overgrown with woods.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he said.
“I felt like, ‘Damn it, I have to go back to real life.’”
