Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent studies suggest the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the intestines make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and at the same time not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the intestines, appear to increase the tolerance of cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan was contained in the diet of mice, the more these immune cells they had.”
He suggested the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barrag<0xC3><0xA1>nvas, studying a variety of immune-boosting cells, found that one group of mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line, but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice—communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice's gut cells was sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but absent in mice without them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and they had immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid—without bacteria—to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have become tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells also halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barrag<0xC3><0xA1>n explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel disease, defects in tryptophan-associated genes have been found.
She says, "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population.”
