Requisites for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to drive a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as “Marine One” when the president is on board, became a central element of the July 17 White House event that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials inspected technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truckloader from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for managing the helicopter, the White House Military Directorate ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an "unusual" event.
“I just wanted you to make sure you were aware because this is an unusual, widely reported press event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at around 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if the departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security guards remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it was not clear whether a second crew was needed in the end.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, the HMX-1 clarified whether the event was inconsistent with this ruling.
“Among other things, we were asked if this was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go,” replied the deputy chief.
The "Made in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event, and Hatch's law did not apply to it.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the health care reform that was in development in the Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking them only for the sake of photo opportunity is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with reports of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ screening, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often conduct training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight made for the “Made in America” event was counted to the crew in the account of the necessary training flights for a month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 additional hours that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, the taxpayers did not bear the costs for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
The representative of the company Sikorsky said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South lawn.
HMX-1 does not record the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Department of Defense’s hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense’s VH-3D reimbursement rate is $24,380 per hour.
The unit’s records show that the aircraft’s time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield based at Quantico Marine Air Force Base in Virginia.
The White House says the real cost of using the helicopter is far below that rate.
“Calculating the cost for taxpayers based on the approximate reimbursement rate is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These indicative rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocation.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, services and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke in favor of using the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things made in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
Therefore, it is absolutely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was not clear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting on the driver’s seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said, “I have three of them.”
