Senior organiser Drew Duffy said: “Our union members are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the facility’s general manager on business needs and the investment plan for the future of Tolcross.”
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and in the territory of Greater Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising subsistence levels and chronic declines in production, the East End of Glasgow desperately needs a flourishing production at McVitie’s factory.
According to the representative of Pladis, “The head of the Tolcross facility only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our constant cooperation with employees and representatives of the trade union.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives in Tolcross, where we discussed a number of issues openly.
We talked to employees about how, like all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions – and this applies to all our facilities and activities – to remain competitive.
“In recent years, we have invested more than <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in our Tolcross facility, especially in production lines and performance improvements.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in the event of any changes in the work at this facility, employees and trade union representatives will be the first to know about it.”
